                    "text": "This is a classic \"avoiding the trap\" situation. Hiding the 95% assumption in an appendix might save you from Marcus momentarily, but it will blow up in your face the moment a board member says, *\"Where is the data for this number?\"* and you have to fumble through an appendix.\n\nIf Marcus is sharp, burying the number just signals that the top number is unearned. You lose your authority.\n\nInstead, use a **\"Range & The Path\"** strategy. This makes you look calculated, not reckless. It shows the board you know the difficulty of the task, but you believe in the *mechanics* of your solution.\n\nHere is how to restructure that slide to sell the number without looking like you are lying.\n\n### The Strategy: \"The Velocity of Adoption\"\n\nDon't present the $2.3B as a single straight line. Present it as a **trajectory**. You are not gambling; you are running a compounding acceleration.\n\n**1. The Slide Structure: The \"Ascent\" Graph**\n\n*   **The Left Axis (Reality):** Show the \"Conservative Baseline\" (80% occupancy).\n    *   This aligns with Marcus’s 70-75% comfort zone. It makes you look responsible.\n*   **The Middle (The Sweet Spot):** Show where you actually think you'll land (90% occupancy).\n*   **The Right Axis (The Vision):** Show the top line ($2.3B).\n*   **The Visual:** Draw a curved line starting at the baseline and arching upward steeply to the $2.3B target.\n\n**2. The Copy/Paste Slide Text**\n\n**Headline: The Compounding Power of Labor-Attached Retail**\n*(Subhead: Why our Year 5 baseline is higher than industry average)*\n\n*   **The Baseline (Standard):** $1.6B Rev (80% Occupancy).\n    *   *Note:* \"Standard retail models rely on foot traffic, not physical presence.\"\n*   **The Thornwell Multiplier:**\n    *   **Year 1:** 65% (Retention & Reconfiguration).\n    *   **Year 2:** 85% (Anchor adoption).\n    *   **Year 3-5:** 95% (Momentum & Ecosystem lock-in).\n*   **The Resulting Run-Rate:** **$2.3B Stabilized Revenue (2028).**\n\n**3. The Narrative Script**\n\nWhen you get to this slide, deliver this line. It turns Marcus’s objection into your advantage:\n\n> \"Marcus is right that the *industry average* for new retail sits around 75% in the first year. That’s because standard retail is fighting for people who are already busy.\n>\n> **We are not 'opening' new retail—we are serving the workforce that is already back.** This creates a different adoption curve. We are starting at the bottom but with a much steeper velocity. The $2.3B isn't a 'heroic assumption'; it’s the math of high-volume, high-frequency use within a captive audience.\"\n\n### Why this works better than the Appendix:\n1.  **It owns the assumption:** You are explicitly saying, \"Yes, we assume 95% by Year 5. Here is exactly how we get there (Year 1, Year 2, Year 3).\"\n2.  **It gives Marcus a bridge:** You aren't asking the board to buy the 95% immediately. You are asking them to buy the *momentum*. Marcus will nod along at the first two years and grudgingly agree with the math by Year 5.\n3.  **It redefines \"Retail\":** You shift the conversation from \"Can we fill a store?\" to \"Are we capturing the spend of the employees already sitting in the building?\"\n\n**Bottom line:** Don't hide the 95%. Showcase the *step-by-step mechanism* that gets you there. It sounds like a strategy, not a wish list."
