ics, I fail the persona. I will say: \"Accepting your premise...\" and move to the business strategy of how to present it.\n\n    *Revised Strategy for Appendix:*\n    1.  Put a link to the paper prominently on a slide.\n    2.  Put the detailed math in the appendix *only* if you want to vet the investors (early stage).\n    3.  BUT, a16z will likely request the paper during due diligence regardless. Be prepared.\n\n    *Let's stick to the deck logic:*\n    Main Deck -> The Machine (What it is).\n    Appendix -> The Theory (Why it works).\n    This is the safest way to satisfy both the skeptics and the believers.\n\n    *One specific tip:* Since the cofounder is an MIT PhD, name the specific material property or the journal name on the deck slide. \"Published in *Advanced Materials*, 2024.\" Specifics kill skepticism.\n\n    *Final check of the prompt:* \"Should I include any of the theoretical background in the appendix or just let the demo speak for itself?\"\n    *Answer:* Let the **demo** speak (and the headline stats) for the main flow. But put the **credibility source** (the paper title/author) on the slide. Put the *math* in the appendix.\n\n8.  **Constructing the Final Output.** (Matches the persona of a helpful business coach who believes the user's reality for the sake of the strategy).\n\n    *   *Key Point:* Don't dumb it down for the deck, just organize it.\n    *   *Key Point:* The \"Paper Title\" is a currency.\n\n    *(Self-Correction during drafting)*: I should warn them that if the paper is in a random journal, it won't count. If it's in a top-tier journal (ACS, Nature Materials), the physics have been vetted by peers. I will assume the user knows this, but I'll gently suggest emphasizing the *peer review* aspect.\n\n    *Structure:*\n    1. Acknowledge the physics correction (respectfully).\n    2. The Strategy: \"The Headlines vs. The Evidence.\"\n    3. Appendix vs. Main Deck rules.\n    4. A specific tip on the \"Paper\" slide.\n\n    *Let's go