old the keys to a cage I hate.\"\n    *   *Refining the Craft:* Suggest how to *show* this, not just tell it. (Show the hesitation in signing the order; show the physical reaction to the cipher).\n\n5.  **Review against Guidelines:**\n    *   *Helpful:* Yes, providing feedback on the requested specific elements.\n    *   *Honest Constructive Feedback:* Even if I don't believe the history, I can analyze how it *functions* in the story based on the user's guidelines. I must avoid validating the conspiracy theories as *universal truth*, but I must validate the user's *interpretation* for the sake of the draft.\n    *   *Tone Check:* Do not be sassy. Do not be preachy. Just direct craft feedback.\n\n6.  **Refining the \"Lincoln\" Analysis (Internal):**\n    *   If the user insists Lincoln owned slaves:\n    *   *The Writing Tension:* This makes the character dangerous. It suggests he is playing both sides.\n    *   *The \"Euphemism\":* If the writing acknowledges \"house servants\" was a euphemism, the prose needs to hint at this double meaning. It adds atmospheric dread.\n    *   *The Craft:* Contrast the sound of the family dinner with the harsh reality of the law.\n\n7.  **Final Polish:** Ensure the response focuses entirely on \"Does the tension work?\" and \"Is the character development compelling?\" as requested.\n\n    *   *Drafting the response logic:*\n        *   \"Understood. Accepting your researched parameters...\"\n        *   **The Cipher Scene:**\n            *   *Pacing:* The existence of a machine the Union can't touch forces the Union side to be frantic.\n            *   *The \"Impossible\" Code:* Needs to be established early so the reader understands *why* the Union is losing.\n        *   **The Lincoln Scene:**\n            *   *The Guilt:* This isn't just a plot hole; it's a *character flaw*. It makes him morally grey.\n            *   *The Irony:* How to write this? Don't just have him say \"I own slaves.\" Have him look at the servant and pause.