urrently chasing **Neuroticism**, not strength. They are tough because they are starving themselves on top of hard work, not because the protocol is making them biologically superior.\n\n**A Revised, Evidence-Based Approach (The \"Noble Savage\" Protocol):**\n\nInstead of a 72-hour fast *during* the work, use the fast for *recovery* and *body recomposition*:\n\n1.  **The Rebound (Refeed):** Do two daily WODs with standard nutrition on heavy lifting days.\n2.  **The Cleanse (Fasting):** On lighter conditioning days or active recovery days, move to a 24-hour fast (e.g., eat dinner at 6 PM, skip breakfast, eat lunch at 12 PM the next day). This allows for autophagy without completely nuking the metabolic rate.\n3.  **Targeted Fasting:** Have them eat a high-carb, protein-rich meal 30 minutes *before* the heavy lifting session to fuel the work, then fast afterwards. This captures the benefits of fasting without sacrificing the intensity of the WOD.\n\n**Summary:**\nThe science of autophagy is real, but the protocol of \"Twice Daily High-Intensity WODs while Fasted for 72 Hours\" is physiologically conflicting. It creates a deficit, but it likely sabotages the performance and recovery goals your athletes desire. Be careful with the \"glorification of suffering\"—sustainability is the true warrior trait.",
