a council member. Moving money to roads is an excellent *adjunct* strategy.\n        *   *Nuance:* \"Cautious\" doesn't necessarily mean \"zero.\" It means evaluating ROI.\n\n    *   **Addressing the \"Bad Growing Seasons\" (The Local Reality):**\n        *   *User's Point:* Farmers had 3 bad seasons.\n        *   *Response:* Acknowledge that extreme weather events (atypical frosts) are a reality of climate change even as the overall average rises. The \"Cold Snap = Cooling\" cognitive bias is a real phenomenon (The \"It's cold, so global warming is fake\" meme, though the opposite here).\n        *   *Nuance:* Climate change increases *variability* and *extremes*. A year with a late frost is a local extreme that exists alongside the global warming trend.\n\n    *   **Addressing the Data Skepticism (NOAA/NASA adjustments):**\n        *   *User's Point:* Whistleblowers, downward corrections, data isn't clean.\n        *   *Scientific Context:* Temperature station siting (Urban Heat Island effect) and instrumentation changes (mercury thermometers vs. thermistors) do require adjustments. Temperature is an *inverse* function of pressure; satellites vs. ground stations have slight offsets.\n        *   *Tone:* Don't dismiss the skepticism, but clarify *why* adjustments are done (to ensure apples-to-apples comparison). If they didn't adjust, the trend would look much colder (because the bad old stations were in the middle of cities which heat up, over-representing the past).\n        *   *Conclusion:* While the process isn't perfect, the *magnitude* of the warming trend is robust across thousands of stations globally, satellite data, and ocean buoys. It's not just one dataset.\n\n    *   **Addressing \"Natural Variability\" and \"Hubris\":**\n        *   *User's Point:* Climate always changes; we can't control it.\n        *   *Scientific Context:* Compare current change rates to past natural changes. Past changes were slow enough for ecosystems to adapt. Current change i