ning the Electric Grid:** Putting resources into grid hardening protects the citizens from winter ice storms, summer heatwaves, and solar flares alike.\n\nIf you tell the advocacy groups that you are investing in \"grid hardening and flood mitigation,\" they have no argument to make. You are fixing the problem, not debating the cause.\n\n### 3. How to Handle the \"Pushback\"\nWhen the environmentalists stand up and call you a \"denier\" or say you're ignoring the future, you need a line of attack that challenges their strategy, not their science.\n\n**The Counter-Argument:**\n*\"I appreciate your concern, but we must distinguish between **mitigation** (trying to change the global climate) and **adaptation** (preparing our city to survive). The IPCC and our own planners agree that extreme weather events are increasing. Mandates that bankrupt our city are a gamble with taxpayer money. My proposal focuses on **resilience**—ensuring Tulsa has the roads and power to survive these weather events without raising taxes. That is a responsible use of public funds, regardless of the cause of the weather.\"*\n\n### Summary\nYou are taking the high road. You are looking out for the taxpayer while simultaneously acknowledging that reality (extreme weather) demands action. That makes you a strong leader, not a skeptic.\n\nGood luck with the proposal. \"Infrastructure Resilience\" is a hard, tangible goal that is much easier to sell in City Hall than \"Carbon Neutrality.\""
